(25, 2, '2010-09-20 13:45:13', '2010-09-20 13:45:13', '<div id="_mcePaste">Day 2 was a leadership facilitation where we worked with an ex-alumni. Throughout the exercise it struck me that leadership issues were all about people and the biggest issues were often based around leaders not facing their own demons or even more commonly, being too close to something to really understand how it was affecting them and they were affecting it.</div>\r\n<div>Often people are caught up so much in the doing that they don’t get the time to revisit some of the key strategic directions, such as where we are going, who are we at the moment and what we would like to be in future. It seems obvious that preventing is cheaper than curing, but without the openness and objectivity it takes longer to get there. Through digging at the base of the issues it therefore seemed imperative that the goals for the individual were not secondary to the goals of the organisation.</div>\r\n<div id="_mcePaste">In reflection, it made me look at my own short, medium and long term plans. Short term (the quick and the dirty)  review skills gaps,  look at marketing, identify who is best fit to help us, get a mentor. Medium term (where we are going) revisiting and adding to the action plan, with big enough milestones to make a difference and with small enough actions to have daily responsibility. Long term (sharing the vision) recommunicating the strategy of the business, whilst meeting and delivering the expectations of the team.</div>\r\n<div id="_mcePaste">I find it amazing how crucial time out of your own organisation is to meet with like-minded and diverse groups to help with your own development of how you see the world.</div>\r\nDay 2 – Common Purpose – A leadership facilitationMonday, March 8th, 2010Day 2 was a leadership facilitation where we worked with an ex-alumni. Throughout the exercise it struck me that leadership issues were all about people and the biggest issues were often based around leaders not facing their own demons or even more commonly, being too close to something to really understand how it was affecting them and they were affecting it.  Often people are caught up so much in the doing that they don’t get the time to revisit some of the key strategic directions, such as where we are going, who are we at the moment and what we would like to be in future. It seems obvious that preventing is cheaper than curing, but without the openness and objectivity it takes longer to get there. Through digging at the base of the issues it therefore seemed imperative that the goals for the individual were not secondary to the goals of the organisation.In reflection, it made me look at my own short, medium and long term plans. Short term (the quick and the dirty)  review skills gaps,  look at marketing, identify who is best fit to help us, get a mentor. Medium term (where we are going) revisiting and adding to the action plan, with big enough milestones to make a difference and with small enough actions to have daily responsibility. Long term (sharing the vision) recommunicating the strategy of the business, whilst meeting and delivering the expectations of the team.I find it amazing how crucial time out of your own organisation is to meet with like-minded and diverse groups to help with your own development of how you see the world.', 'Day 2 – Common Purpose – A leadership facilitation', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '18-revision-6', '', '', '2010-09-20 13:45:13', '2010-09-20 13:45:13', '', 18, 'http://www.sherpabusinessconsultancy.com/wordpress/?p=25', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(27, 2, '2010-09-20 13:42:59', '2010-09-20 13:42:59', '<div id="_mcePaste">Day 1 and it certainly felt a bit like being a kid on my first day at school, but I had a pretty open mind as to who or what I may discover.  The day was full of interesting conversations, different objectives and hopes for what people may get from the experience.  There were numerous talks and workshops that helped position the content and develop relationships with the new alumni.</div>\r\n<div id="_mcePaste">The talk that really stood out to me was delivered by Dr Bill Lancaster.  Bill helped me understand two things; 1) why my Mother still nags me – due to women holding the role of ‘policewoman’ in the family since the 1600’s, still apparent in my family! 2) The Bigg Market ethos and the reasons why us Geordies wear short sleeved shirts and mini skirts in the winter – all down to the prosperous times of ‘flashy lads and lasses’ from back in the shipyards and heavy industry era.</div>\r\n<div id="_mcePaste">I think the main thing that I observed that day was motivation for leadership and purpose.  All of the people I spoke to regarding purpose had a negative experience either in school or their career.  This has acted almost as a catalyst of extreme motivation to achieve something based on strong values and beliefs.  I was quite moved by the level of motivation and determination to really make a difference to the people’s lives they could affect.</div>\r\n<div id="_mcePaste">It has made me question, as to my own journey regarding what I am trying to achieve.   I have a clear direction of where I am going, but what I deem as ‘achievement’ is still a question I need to explore.  With the word ‘achievement’ like I found on the first day the meaning of words can be very different from person to person.</div>', 'Common Purpose – The Sage – Day 1 – Plotting the Course', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '11-revision-6', '', '', '2010-09-20 13:42:59', '2010-09-20 13:42:59', '', 11, 'http://www.sherpabusinessconsultancy.com/wordpress/?p=27', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
